COMMENT_ASSESS: THIS IS A BEAUTIFUL LAKE WITH GREAT WATER QUALITY AND A LONG TRACT OF UNDEVELOPED SHORELINE. THERE IS AT LEAST ONE LARGE RESORT AND GOLF COURSE ON SOUTH SIDE. SIGN AT LAUNCH INDICATES THE PRESENCE OF RUSTY CRAYFISH (AN INVASIVE.)

GENERAL_ASSESSMENT: LAKE SEEMS TO SUPPORT A VERY HEALTHY FISH AND BIRD COMMUNITY. SAW DEAD 6-7 LB BASS ON SHORE OF BOAT RAMP FROM ANGLING.
WILDLIFE: AMERICAN EGRETS HAVE VERY LARGE ROKERY IN UPPER REACH NEAR G. GREAT BLUE HERONS, NORNED LIZZARD NEAR BOAT RAMP. FLOCK OF WHITE PELICANS AT H.
VISUAL_ASSESSMENT: LAKE STARTED OUT PRETTY CLEAR, BUT BECAME TURBID WITH RAIN.
ALGAL_ABUNDANCE: VERY LITTLE ALGAE ALONG SOME MARGINS OF SHORELINE.
NUTRIENT_SOURCES: SOME LIVESTOCK WATERING AT LAKE AND ROW CROPS IN PLACES.
CONDITIONS: FISHING APPEARED TO BE GOOD ON DAY WE SAMPLED. LOOKS LIKE A GOOD LAKE FOR FISHING MORE THAN WATER SKIING.
OBSERVATIONS: SAW NUMEROUS TROTLINES FOR FISH. A FEW FISHING PIERS. ONLY ONE CONCRETE BOAT RAMP. SOME CAMP SITES WITH SWIMMING ACCESS NEAR SHORE, BUT FEW.
COMMENT_ASSESS: LAKE IS EXTREMELY HIGH TO ALMOST FLOOD STAGE. MANY PARTS OF LAKE ARE NOW FRINGED WITH INUNDATED TREES, SHRUBS, AND GRASSES. MOST INUNDATED TREES ARE WILLOWS AND MESQUITES. WATER BECAME VERY TURBID AT UPPER END OF LAKE DUE TO RAIN AND CLOSE PROXIMITY OF PLOWED FIELDS. LARGE BEAUTIFUL ROOKERY OF AMERICAN EGRETS AT FAR UPPER CHANNEL AT UPSTREAM END OF RESERVOIR.

WILDLIFE: WADING BIRD ROOKERY, FISH, PELICANS
VISUAL_ASSESSMENT: TURBIDITY DUE TO HIGH RAINFALL THIS YEAR.

GENERAL_ASSESSMENT: NARROW RESERVOIR WITH GENERALLY STEEP BANKS. HIGHLY DEVELOPED LAKE, SO HIGH BOAT AND WAVE ACTION DISTURBANCE POSSIBILITY.
WILDLIFE: DUCKS, GEESE, BLUEGILL, BASS, VULTURES, BLUE HERON.

OBSERVATIONS: LOW BOAT TRAFFIC OBSERVED BUT HIGH POTENTIAL. NESTING BLUE GILL OBSERVED. APPEARS TO BE LARGE PANFISH POPULATION.

GENERAL_ASSESSMENT: WEATHER - MOSTLY CLOUDY, SLIGHT BREEZE. TEMP ABOUT 25C. THIS IS A NATURAL LAKE. NO INLETS EXCEPT GROUNDWATER.

LAKE IS SPRING FED, NO INLETS. DAM IS ABOUT 6FT (BACK SIDE OF DAM). FISH LARGEMOUTH BASS, BULLHEADS, BLACK CRAPPIE, PUMPKINSEEDS, BLUEGILLS, CHAIN PICHERED (?). GOOSE DROPPINGS ON SOME LAWNS - FLOCK OF ABOUT 21. INCLUDES HATCH (ABOUT 2 SETS). A FEW OF THE LAWNS ARE MOWED TO LAKE. APPEARS WELL MANAGED.

WILDLIFE: SONGBIRDS, LOONS, MERGANSER, SEAGULLS

COMMENT_ASSESS: THIS RESERVOIR LIKELY OFFERS GOOD FISHING AND WATERFOWL HUNTING OPPORTUNITIES WHEN WATER LEVEL IS NORMAL OR NEAR FULL. THE LOW WATER LEVEL PRESENT IS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE RELATIVE DISTURBANCE ASSOCIATED WITH THIS WATERBODY. THE CONDITIONS OBSERVED AT THIS RESERVOIR IS TYPICAL OF MANY SIMILAR RESERVOIRS IN THE AREA.

COMMENT_ASSESS: LAKE IS 2768 ACRES AND 38 FT DEEP. IM 1985 THE REGULATIONS WERE CHANGED TO PROTECT SPAWNING RAINBOW TROUT, LIMITS WERE REDUCED TO 5 FISH. LAKE IS STOCKED WITH 4 INCH RAINBOW TROUT, BUT ALL OTHER SPECIES REMAIN SELF-SUSTAINING. THIS IS A POPULAR RECREATION AREA, ESPECIALLY FOR FISHING. IN JUNE, THE DENSITY OF PEOPLE RECREATING ON THE LAKE WAS LOW.

THIS NATURAL DRAINING IS CAUSING CONTROVERSY AS DEVILS LAKE WATERS ARE MAKING THEIR WAY TO THE RED RIVER OF THE NORTH BETWEEN DAKOTA AND MINNESOTA AND EVENTUALLY TO CANADA AND THE HUDSON BAY. LYNGBYA AND OTHER ALGAE ABUNDANT AT J AND VICINITY DUE TO SEPTIC / SANDMOUND PROXIMITY AND PROBABLY LEAKAGE. LAKE SHORELINE AWAY FROM CAMP WAS MORE TYPICAL OF NA

A DIKE WAS BUILT IN THE 1930'S TO ENHANCE LAKE FOR RECREATION AND TO PREVENT DRAINAGE. SINKHOLES USED TO DRAIN LAKE IN LOW WATER YEARS UNTIL DIKE WAS BUILT. TRANSECT C HAS AN UNUSUAL VERTICAL DEPTH TO HIGH WATER MARK DUE TO SPILLWAY IN RELATION TO SINKHOLES.

A DAM WAS BUILD ACROSS THE TARN OUTLET IN THE 1920'S TO RETAIN WATER FOR IRRIGATION. PERHAPS A DOZEN TROUT SEEN IN VARIOUS STAGES OF DEATH. SEVERAL DESSICATED ON THE SHORE.
